{"title_page": "Estelle Reiner", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Estelle Reiner\n| image          = Estelle Reiner.jpg\n| birthname      = Estelle Lebost\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1914|6|5|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[The Bronx]], [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2008|10|25|1914|6|5|mf=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place  = [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| occupation     = Actress, singer\n| years_active   = 1960\u20131989\n| spouse         = {{Marriage|[[Carl Reiner]]|1943<!--Omission per Template:Marriage instructions-->}}\n| children       = [[Rob Reiner|Rob]]<br />[[Annie Reiner|Annie]]<br />[[Lucas Reiner|Lucas]]\n}}\n\n'''Estelle Reiner''' ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Lebost'''; June 5, 1914 &ndash; October 25, 2008) was an American actress and singer, described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"matriarch of one of the leading families in American comedy\". She was the wife of [[Carl Reiner]] and the mother of [[Rob Reiner]].\n\n==Life and career==\nReiner was born in the Bronx, New York City, and graduated from [[James Monroe High School (New York)|James Monroe High School]]. She was a visual artist and met her future husband, Carl Reiner, while she was working in the [[Catskill Mountains|Catskills]], designing stage sets for hotel shows. She married Reiner in 1943, and had three children [[Rob Reiner|Rob]], Lucas and [[Annie Reiner|Annie]].<ref name=NYTObit/> She was Jewish.\n\nCarl Reiner's 1960s television comedy, ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'', recapitulated his career writing for [[Sid Caesar]], with Carl Reiner playing the Caesar character and [[Dick Van Dyke]] portraying Reiner's real-life job as a writer in the role of Rob Petrie. The re-creation was so complete that the Petries in the show lived on Bonnie Meadow Road in suburban [[New Rochelle, New York]], the same street as the real-life Reiners. As described by Rob Reiner, \"Basically he wrote his own life\" in ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'' and that his \"mother was [[Mary Tyler Moore]]\".<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nIn her 60s, Reiner became a cabaret singer and performed for decades, until just a few years before her death. She studied the theatre with [[method acting]] pioneer [[Lee Strasberg]] and with [[Viola Spolin]], the American Grandmother of Improvisation. She appeared in a number of film comedies, including the 1980 film ''[[Fatso (1980 film)|Fatso]]'' with [[Dom DeLuise]] as Mrs. Goodman, and in the 1983 movies ''[[The Man With Two Brains]]'' with [[Steve Martin]] in the role \"Tourist in Elevator\" and in [[Mel Brooks]]' ''[[To Be or Not to Be (1983 film)|To Be or Not to Be]]'' as Gruba.<ref name=NYTObit/><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0717995/ Estelle Reiner], [[Internet Movie Database]]. Accessed October 30, 2008.</ref>\n\nReiner's most enduring film role was in 1989's ''[[When Harry Met Sally...]]'', in which director Rob Reiner cast his mother as a customer in a scene with stars [[Billy Crystal]] and [[Meg Ryan]] at [[Katz's Delicatessen]], in which Ryan fakes what was described as \"a very public (and very persuasive) orgasm\". Approached by a waitress after Ryan finishes, Reiner deadpans \"I\u2019ll have what she\u2019s having\". The line was ranked 33rd on the [[American Film Institute]]'s list of the [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movie Quotes|Top 100 movie quotations]], just behind ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'''s \"Round up the usual suspects\".<ref name=NYTObit/><ref>[http://www.afi.com/docs/tvevents/pdf/quotes100.pdf AFI\u2019s 100 Years: 100 Movie Quotes], [[American Film Institute]], page 2. Accessed October 30, 2008.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nReiner died of natural causes on October 25, 2008 in her home in [[Beverly Hills, California]]. She was 94.<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite news|author=Weber, Bruce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/30/movies/30reiner.html |title=Estelle Reiner, 94, Comedy Matriarch, Is Dead|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 29, 2008|access-date=October 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n*''[[Fatso (1980 film)|Fatso]]'' (1980) - Mrs. Goodman\n*''[[The Man with Two Brains]]'' (1983) - Tourist in Elevator\n*''[[To Be or Not to Be (1983 film)|To Be or Not to Be]]'' (1983) - Gruba\n*''[[Hot to Trot]]'' (1988) - Mrs. Goldblatt\n*''[[When Harry Met Sally...]]'' (1989) - Older Woman Customer (final film role)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0717995}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reiner, Estelle}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Singers from California]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:James Monroe High School (New York City) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Estelle Reiner\n| image          = Estelle Reiner.jpg\n| birthname      = Estelle Lebost\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1914|6|5|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[The Bronx]], [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2008|10|25|1914|6|5|mf=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place  = [[Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| occupation     = Actress, singer\n| years_active   = 1960\u20131989\n| spouse         = {{Marriage|[[Carl Reiner]]|1943<!--Omission per Template:Marriage instructions-->}}\n| children       = [[Rob Reiner|Rob]]<br />[[Annie Reiner|Annie]]<br />[[Lucas Reiner|Lucas]]\n}}\n\n'''Estelle Reiner''' ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Lebost'''; June 5, 1914 &ndash; October 25, 2008) was an American actress and singer, described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"matriarch of one of the leading families in American comedy\". She was the wife of [[Carl Reiner]] and the mother of [[Rob Reiner]].\n\n==Life and career==\nReiner was born in the Bronx, New York City, and graduated from [[James Monroe High School (New York)|James Monroe High School]]. She was a visual artist and met her future husband, Carl Reiner, while she was working in the [[Catskill Mountains|Catskills]], designing stage sets for hotel shows. She married Reiner in 1943, and had three children [[Rob Reiner|Rob]], Lucas and [[Annie Reiner|Annie]].<ref name=NYTObit/> She was Jewish.\n\nCarl Reiner's 1960s television comedy, ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'', recapitulated his career writing for [[Sid Caesar]], with Carl Reiner playing the Caesar character and [[Dick Van Dyke]] portraying Reiner's real-life job as a writer in the role of Rob Petrie. The re-creation was so complete that the Petries in the show lived on Bonnie Meadow Road in suburban [[New Rochelle, New York]], the same street as the real-life Reiners. As described by Rob Reiner, \"Basically he wrote his own life\" in ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'' and that his \"mother was [[Mary Tyler Moore]]\".<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\nIn her 60s, Reiner became a cabaret singer and performed for decades, until just a few years before her death. She studied the theatre with [[method acting]] pioneer [[Lee Strasberg]] and with [[Viola Spolin]], the American Grandmother of Improvisation. She appeared in a number of film comedies, including the 1980 film ''[[Fatso (1980 film)|Fatso]]'' with [[Dom DeLuise]] as Mrs. Goodman, and in the 1983 movies ''[[The Man With Two Brains]]'' with [[Steve Martin]] in the role \"Tourist in Elevator\" and in [[Mel Brooks]]' ''[[To Be or Not to Be (1983 film)|To Be or Not to Be]]'' as Gruba.<ref name=NYTObit/><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0717995/ Estelle Reiner], [[Internet Movie Database]]. Accessed October 30, 2008.</ref>\n\nReiner's most enduring film role was in 1989's ''[[When Harry Met Sally...]]'', in which director Rob Reiner cast his mother as a customer in a scene with stars [[Billy Crystal]] and [[Meg Ryan]] at [[Katz's Delicatessen]], in which Ryan fakes what was described as \"a very public (and very persuasive) orgasm\". Approached by a waitress after Ryan finishes, Reiner deadpans \"I\u2019ll have what she\u2019s having\". The line was ranked 33rd on the [[American Film Institute]]'s list of the [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movie Quotes|Top 100 movie quotations]], just behind ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'''s \"Round up the usual suspects\".<ref name=NYTObit/><ref>[http://www.afi.com/docs/tvevents/pdf/quotes100.pdf AFI\u2019s 100 Years: 100 Movie Quotes], [[American Film Institute]], page 2. Accessed October 30, 2008.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nReiner died of natural causes on October 25, 2008 in her home in [[Beverly Hills, California]]. She was 94.<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite news|author=Weber, Bruce|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/30/movies/30reiner.html |title=Estelle Reiner, 94, Comedy Matriarch, Is Dead|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 29, 2008|access-date=October 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Partial filmography==\n*''[[Fatso (1980 film)|Fatso]]'' (1980) - Mrs. Goodman\n*''[[The Man with Two Brains]]'' (1983) - Tourist in Elevator\n*''[[To Be or Not to Be (1983 film)|To Be or Not to Be]]'' (1983) - Gruba\n*''[[Hot to Trot]]'' (1988) - Mrs. Goldblatt\n*''[[When Harry Met Sally...]]'' (1989) - Older Woman Customer (final film role)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0717995}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reiner, Estelle}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Singers from California]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Sinai Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:James Monroe High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:Reiner family]]\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:Reiner family-- Please use only categories which actually exist.  SeeWP:REDNOTusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estelle_Reiner"}
