1 (translation); 222\u2013229 (notes)</ref>\n}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation|last=Hull |first=Eleanor |authorlink=Eleanor Hull |title=The Silver Bough in Irish Legend |journal=Folk-Lore |volume=12 | number=4 |date=December 1901 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2yTjdVKxQP0C&pg=PA436 |pages=431\u2013445 |jstor=1253964}}\n* MacKillop, James (1998) ''Dictionary of Celtic Mythology'', Oxford, Oxford University Press, pp. 21 \"apple\", 205 \"Fand\", 270 \"Imram Brain\", 322\u20133 \"Manann\u00e1n mac Lir\", 346\u3000\"Niam (3)\", 359\u201360 \"Otherworld\". {{ISBN|0-19-280120-1}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/celt/ffcc/ffcc260.htm Internet Sacred Text Archive/Celtic Folklore/The Fairy-Faith in Celtic Countries/Section II, The Recorded Fairy-Faith]\n* [http://www.manannan.net/ Temple of Manannan]\n* [http://www.maryjones.us/index.html Celtic Literature Collective and Jones's Celtic Encyclopedia]\n* [http://www.luminarium.org/mythology/ireland/index.html Irish Literature, Mythology, Folklore, and Drama]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/TheSilverBranchFilm/]\n\n[[Category:Celtic mythology]]\n[[Category:Early Irish literature]]\n[[Category:Irish mythology]]\n[[Category:Symbols]]\n", "name_user": "Bard Cadarn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Echtra Cormaic to the opening section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silver_Branch"}
{"title_page": "Chicxulub impactor", "text_new": "{{short description|Asteroid implicated in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs}}\n[[File:Chicxulub-Anomaly.jpg|thumb|May 2003 sketch of the gravity anomaly map of the [[Chicxulub crater]] area. Red and yellow are gravity highs, green and blue are gravity lows, white indicates [[sinkhole]]s, or \"[[cenote]]s\", and the shaded area is the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]].<ref>Nicholas M. Short, Sr., [http://rst.gsfc.nasa.gov/Sect18/Sect18_4.html Crater Morphology Some Characteristic Impact Structures] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204072914/http://rst.gsfc.nasa.gov/Sect18/Sect18_4.html# |date=2012-02-04 }} at nasa.gov, accessed January 2013</ref><ref>The article by Nicholas M. Short, Sr. appears to have moved, but the image above does not appear to have moved with it. See [https://fas.org/irp/imint/docs/rst/Sect18/Sect18_4.html Crater Morphology Some Characteristic Impact Structures] at fas.org, Accessed December 9, 2015.</ref>]]\n\nThe '''Chicxulub impactor''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t\u0283|i\u02d0|k|\u0283|\u0259|l|u\u02d0|b}} {{respell|CHEEK|sh\u0259-loob}}), also known as the '''K/Pg impactor''' and (more speculatively) as the '''Chicxulub asteroid''', was an [[asteroid]] or other [[celestial body]] some {{convert|11|to|81|km|0}} in diameter and having a mass between {{val|1.0|e=15}} and {{val|4.6|e=17|u=kg}},<ref name=\"DMCT2014\">{{cite arxiv|last1=Durand-Manterola|first1=H. J.|last2=Cordero-Tercero|first2=G.|title=Assessments of the energy, mass and size of the Chicxulub Impactor|year=2014|eprint=1403.6391|class=astro-ph.EP}}</ref> which struck the Earth at a velocity of roughly 20 kilometers per second<Ref>[https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2010/03/04/asteroid-terminated-dinosaur-era-in-a-matter-of-days/ Asteroid terminated dinosaur era in a matter of days]. National Geographic. March 4, 2010.</ref> at the end of the [[Cretaceous|Cretaceous period]], 66 [[Myr|million years ago]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Dinosaur extinction: Scientists estimate 'most accurate' date|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-21379024|website = BBC News|accessdate = 2015-10-28|date = 2013-02-08}}</ref> creating the [[Chicxulub crater]]. It impacted a few kilometres from the present-day town of [[Chicxulub, Yucat\u00e1n|Chicxulub]] in [[Mexico]], after which the impactor and its crater are named. Because the estimated date of the object's impact and the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene boundary]] (K\u2013Pg boundary) coincide, there is a scientific consensus that its impact was the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event]] which caused the death of the planet's non-[[bird|avian]] [[dinosaur]]s and many other species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = International Consensus \u2014 Link Between Asteroid Impact and Mass Extinction Is Rock Solid|url = http://www.lpi.usra.edu/features/chicxulub/|website = www.lpi.usra.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-28}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|url=http://eesc.columbia.edu/courses/w4937/Readings/Schulte.etal.2010.pdf |title=The Chicxulub Asteroid Impact and Mass Extinction at the Cretaceous-Paleogene Boundary |last=Schulte |first=Peter |date=March 5, 2010 |journal=Science |doi=10.1126/science.1177265 |pmid=20203042 |access-date=2015-06-25 |volume=327 |issue=5970 |pages=1214\u20138 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625001637/http://eesc.columbia.edu/courses/w4937/Readings/Schulte.etal.2010.pdf |archivedate=June 25, 2015 |bibcode = 2010Sci...327.1214S }}</ref> In October 2019, researchers reported that the event rapidly [[Ocean acidification|acidified the oceans]] producing [[ecological collapse]] and long-lasting effects on the climate, and, accordingly, was a key reason for the Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene [[extinction event]].<ref name=\"NYT-20191021\">{{cite news |last=Joel |first=Lucas |title=The Dinosaur-Killing Asteroid Acidified the Ocean in a Flash - The Chicxulub event was as damaging to life in the oceans as it was to creatures on land, a study shows. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/21/science/chicxulub-asteroid-ocean-acid.html |date=21 October 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=22 October 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"PNAS-20191021\">{{cite journal |author=Henehan, Michael J. |display-authors=et al. |title=Rapid ocean acidification and protracted Earth system recovery followed the end-Cretaceous Chicxulub impact |date=21 October 2019 |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |volume=116 |issue=45 |pages=22500\u201322504 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1905989116  |pmid=31636204 |pmc=6842625 |bibcode=2019PNAS..11622500H }}</ref>\n\nThe impactor's crater is over {{convert|150|km|abbr=off}} in diameter<ref name=\"eid\">{{Cite Earth Impact DB | name = Chicxulub | accessdate = December 30, 2008 }}</ref> making it [[List of impact craters on Earth#Largest craters (10 Ma or more)|one of the largest]] known [[impact crater]]s on Earth.\n\n==Parent body==\nSeveral competing models for the impactor's origin exist, and for its relationship to other asteroids that continue to exist in the Solar System. In September 2007, [[William F. Bottke]], David Vokrouhlick\u00fd, and David Nesvorn\u00fd proposed an origin for the impactor in an article published in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''. They argued that a collision in the asteroid belt 160 million years ago resulted in the [[Baptistina family]] of asteroids, the largest surviving member of which is [[298 Baptistina]]. They proposed that the Chicxulub impactor was an asteroid member of this group, referring to the large amount of carbonaceous material present in microscopic fragments at the site, suggesting that it was a member of a rare class of asteroids called [[carbonaceous chondrite]]s, like Baptistina. According to Bottke, the Chicxulub impactor was a fragment of a much larger parent body about {{convert|170|km|mi|abbr=on}} across, with the impacting body being around 6&nbsp;km (4&nbsp;mi) in diameter.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nHowever, in 2011 new data from the [[Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer]] revised the date of the collision which created the [[Baptistina family]] to about 80 million years ago, casting doubt on the hypothesis, as typically the process of resonance and collision of an asteroid takes many tens of millions of years.<ref name=Universe>Tammy Plotner, ''[http://www.universetoday.com/89050/did-asteroid-baptistina-kill-the-dinosaurs-think-other-wise/#more-89050 Did Asteroid Baptistina Kill the Dinosaurs? Think other WISE...]'' in ''Universe Today'' (2011) at universetoday.com</ref>\n\nOther work has associated the asteroid [[P/2010 A2]], a member of the [[Flora family]] of asteroids, as a possible remnant cohort of the Chicxulub impactor.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/02/02/us-space-asteroid-idUSTRE61154120100202 \"Smashed asteroids may be related to dinosaur killer\"] Reuters, February 2, 2010</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Astronomy|Geology|Palaeontology|Biology|Dinosaurs|Mexico}}\n* [[Alvarez hypothesis]]\n* [[Timeline of Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event research]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{KT_boundary|K-Pg boundary}}\n{{Impact cratering on Earth}}\n\n{{coord|21|24|N|89|31|W|region:MX-YUC_type:landmark_scale:5000000|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicxulub Asteroid}}\n[[Category:Asteroids]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9rida, Yucat\u00e1n]]\n[[Category:Extinction events]]\n[[Category:Geological history of Earth]]\n[[Category:Natural history of the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Impact events]]\n[[Category:Ancient natural disasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Asteroid implicated in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs}}\n[[File:Chicxulub-Anomaly.jpg|thumb|May 2003 sketch of the gravity anomaly map of the [[Chicxulub crater]] area. Red and yellow are gravity highs, green and blue are gravity lows, white indicates [[sinkhole]]s, or \"[[cenote]]s\", and the shaded area is the [[Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]].<ref>Nicholas M. Short, Sr., [http://rst.gsfc.nasa.gov/Sect18/Sect18_4.html Crater Morphology Some Characteristic Impact Structures] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204072914/http://rst.gsfc.nasa.gov/Sect18/Sect18_4.html# |date=2012-02-04 }} at nasa.gov, accessed January 2013</ref><ref>The article by Nicholas M. Short, Sr. appears to have moved, but the image above does not appear to have moved with it. See [https://fas.org/irp/imint/docs/rst/Sect18/Sect18_4.html Crater Morphology Some Characteristic Impact Structures] at fas.org, Accessed December 9, 2015.</ref>]]\n\nThe '''Chicxulub impactor''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t\u0283|i\u02d0|k|\u0283|\u0259|l|u\u02d0|b}} {{respell|CHEEK|sh\u0259-loob}}), also known as the '''K/Pg impactor''' and (more speculatively) as the '''Chicxulub asteroid''', was an [[asteroid]] or other [[celestial body]] some {{convert|11|to|81|km|0}} in diameter and having a mass between {{val|1.0|e=15}} and {{val|4.6|e=17|u=kg}},<ref name=\"DMCT2014\">{{cite arxiv|last1=Durand-Manterola|first1=H. J.|last2=Cordero-Tercero|first2=G.|title=Assessments of the energy, mass and size of the Chicxulub Impactor|year=2014|eprint=1403.6391|class=astro-ph.EP}}</ref> which struck the Earth at a velocity of roughly 20 kilometers per second<Ref>[https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2010/03/04/asteroid-terminated-dinosaur-era-in-a-matter-of-days/ Asteroid terminated dinosaur era in a matter of days]. National Geographic. March 4, 2010.</ref> at the end of the [[Cretaceous|Cretaceous period]], 66 [[Myr|million years ago]],<ref>{{Cite news|title = Dinosaur extinction: Scientists estimate 'most accurate' date|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-21379024|website = BBC News|accessdate = 2015-10-28|date = 2013-02-08}}</ref> creating the [[Chicxulub crater]]. It impacted a few kilometres from the present-day town of [[Chicxulub, Yucat\u00e1n|Chicxulub]] in [[Mexico]], after which the impactor and its crater are named. Because the estimated date of the object's impact and the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene boundary]] (K\u2013Pg boundary) coincide, there is a scientific consensus that its impact was the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event]] which caused the death of the planet's non-[[bird|avian]] [[dinosaur]]s and many other species.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = International Consensus \u2014 Link Between Asteroid Impact and Mass Extinction Is Rock Solid|url = http://www.lpi.usra.edu/features/chicxulub/|website = www.lpi.usra.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-28}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|url=http://eesc.columbia.edu/courses/w4937/Readings/Schulte.etal.2010.pdf |title=The Chicxulub Asteroid Impact and Mass Extinction at the Cretaceous-Paleogene Boundary |last=Schulte |first=Peter |date=March 5, 2010 |journal=Science |doi=10.1126/science.1177265 |pmid=20203042 |access-date=2015-06-25 |volume=327 |issue=5970 |pages=1214\u20138 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625001637/http://eesc.columbia.edu/courses/w4937/Readings/Schulte.etal.2010.pdf |archivedate=June 25, 2015 |bibcode = 2010Sci...327.1214S }}</ref> In October 2019, researchers reported that the event rapidly [[Ocean acidification|acidified the oceans]] producing [[ecological collapse]] and long-lasting effects on the climate, and, accordingly, was a key reason for the Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene [[extinction event]].<ref name=\"NYT-20191021\">{{cite news |last=Joel |first=Lucas |title=The Dinosaur-Killing Asteroid Acidified the Ocean in a Flash - The Chicxulub event was as damaging to life in the oceans as it was to creatures on land, a study shows. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/21/science/chicxulub-asteroid-ocean-acid.html |date=21 October 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=22 October 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"PNAS-20191021\">{{cite journal |author=Henehan, Michael J. |display-authors=et al. |title=Rapid ocean acidification and protracted Earth system recovery followed the end-Cretaceous Chicxulub impact |date=21 October 2019 |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |volume=116 |issue=45 |pages=22500\u201322504 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1905989116  |pmid=31636204 |pmc=6842625 |bibcode=2019PNAS..11622500H }}</ref>\n\nThe impactor's crater is over {{convert|150|km|abbr=off}} in diameter<ref name=\"eid\">{{Cite Earth Impact DB | name = Chicxulub | accessdate = December 30, 2008 }}</ref> making it [[List of impact craters on Earth#Largest craters (10 Ma or more)|one of the largest]] known [[impact crater]]s on Earth.\n\n==Parent body==\nSeveral competing models for the impactor's origin exist and for its relationship to other asteroids that continue to exist in the Solar System. In September 2007, [[William F. Bottke]], David Vokrouhlick\u00fd, and David Nesvorn\u00fd proposed an origin for the impactor in an article published in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''. They argued that a collision in the asteroid belt 160 million years ago resulted in the [[Baptistina family]] of asteroids, the largest surviving member of which is [[298 Baptistina]]. They proposed that the Chicxulub impactor was an asteroid member of this group, referring to the large amount of carbonaceous material present in microscopic fragments at the site, suggesting that it was a member of a rare class of asteroids called [[carbonaceous chondrite]]s, like Baptistina. According to Bottke, the Chicxulub impactor was a fragment of a much larger parent body about {{convert|170|km|mi|abbr=on}} across, with the impacting body being around 6&nbsp;km (4&nbsp;mi) in diameter.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nHowever, in 2011 new data from the [[Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer]] revised the date of the collision which created the [[Baptistina family]] to about 80 million years ago, casting doubt on the hypothesis, as typically the process of resonance and collision of an asteroid takes many tens of millions of years.<ref name=Universe>Tammy Plotner, ''[http://www.universetoday.com/89050/did-asteroid-baptistina-kill-the-dinosaurs-think-other-wise/#more-89050 Did Asteroid Baptistina Kill the Dinosaurs? Think other WISE...]'' in ''Universe Today'' (2011) at universetoday.com</ref>\n\nOther work has associated the asteroid [[P/2010 A2]], a member of the [[Flora family]] of asteroids, as a possible remnant cohort of the Chicxulub impactor.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/02/02/us-space-asteroid-idUSTRE61154120100202 \"Smashed asteroids may be related to dinosaur killer\"] Reuters, February 2, 2010</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Astronomy|Geology|Palaeontology|Biology|Dinosaurs|Mexico}}\n* [[Alvarez hypothesis]]\n* [[Timeline of Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event research]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{KT_boundary|K-Pg boundary}}\n{{Impact cratering on Earth}}\n\n{{coord|21|24|N|89|31|W|region:MX-YUC_type:landmark_scale:5000000|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chicxulub Asteroid}}\n[[Category:Asteroids]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9rida, Yucat\u00e1n]]\n[[Category:Extinction events]]\n[[Category:Geological history of Earth]]\n[[Category:Natural history of the Yucat\u00e1n Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Impact events]]\n[[Category:Ancient natural disasters]]\n", "name_user": "Rowellcf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParent body", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicxulub_impactor"}
{"title_page": "List of serving generals of the Bangladesh Army", "text_new": "This is a list of the serving generals of the [[Bangladesh Army]].\n\nCurrently the army has one full general, five Lieutenant-Generals and fifty Major-Generals post.\n\n==Current Bangladesh Army  Generals==\n*'''General''' [[File:Four star.jpg|75px]]\n# [[General]] [[Aziz Ahmed (general)|Aziz Ahmed]] \u2013 [[Chief of Army Staff (Bangladesh)|Chief of Army Staff]] ('''CAS'''), Army Headquarters, [[Dhaka Cantonment]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.army.mil.bd/Chief-of-Army-Staff|title=Chief of Army Staff \u2013 Bangladesh Army|website=www.army.mil.bd|language=en|access-date=2018-07-20}}</ref> (also [[Colonel of the Regiment]] \u2013 The East Bengal Regiment; Bangladesh Infantry Regiment; Regiment of Artillery; [[Colonel commandant|Colonel Commandant]] - Armoured Corps; Corps of Engineers ) - 8th [[Bangladesh Military Academy|BMA]] Long Course\n*'''Lieutenant-Generals''' [[File:Three star.jpg|70px]]\n# [[Lieutenant General]] [[Md Mahfuzur Rahman|Md. Mahfuzur Rahman]]  - [[Principal Staff Officer (Bangladesh)|Principal Staff Officer]], [[Armed Forces Division]] ('''PSO AFD'''), [[Prime Minister's Office (Bangladesh)|Prime Minister's Office]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afd.gov.bd/media-center/important-occations/22-sidebar/45-lieutenant-general-md-mahfuzur-rahman-rcds-ndc-afwc-psc-phd.html|title=Lieutenant General Md Mahfuzur Rahman,rcds, ndc,  afwc, psc, PhD|last=Division|first=Armed Forces|website=www.afd.gov.bd|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720195120/https://www.afd.gov.bd/media-center/important-occations/22-sidebar/45-lieutenant-general-md-mahfuzur-rahman-rcds-ndc-afwc-psc-phd.html|archive-date=2018-07-20|url-status=dead}}</ref> - 5th BMA Long Course\n# Lieutenant General [[Shafiqur Rahman (officer)|Shafiqur Rahman]] \u2013 [[Chief of the General Staff]] ('''CGS'''), Army Headquarters, Dhaka Cantonment <ref name=\"Shafiqur\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/160187|title=Shafiqur made CGS, Mujibur new DG of SSF|website=theindependentbd.com|date=July 31, 2018|accessdate=August 2, 2018}}</ref> - 11th BMA Long Course\n# Lieutenant General [[Shamsul Haque (general)|Shamsul Haque]] \u2013 [[Quartermaster general|Quartermaster-General]] ('''QMG'''), Army Headquarters, Dhaka Cantonment - 10th BMA Long Course\n# Lieutenant General [[Shafiuddin Ahmed (officer)|Shafiuddin Ahmed]]  \u2013 [[General officer commanding|General Officer Commanding]], [[ARTDOC|Army Training and Doctrine Command]] ('''GOC ARTDOC'''), [[Mymensingh Cantonment]]<ref name=\"Shafiqur\"/>- 9th BMA Long Course <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyasianage.com/news/192652/shafiuddin-promoted-to-lieutenant-general|title=GOC ARTDOC|website=dailyasianage.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n# Lieutenant General [[Sheikh Mamun Khaled]] - [[Commandant]], [[National Defence College (Bangladesh)|National Defence College]] ('''Commandant, NDC'''), [[Mirpur Cantonment]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ndc.gov.bd/Page/FacultyStaff/Staff/1|title=National Defence College|website=ndc.gov.bd|language=en|access-date=2018-07-20}}</ref> (also Colonel Commandant - Corps of Signals) - 5th BMA Long Course\n#\n#\n*'''Major-Generals''' [[File:Two star.jpg|65px]]\n#[[Major General]] [[Enayet Ullah]]  - [[Adjutant general|Adjutant General]] '''(AG)''', Army Headquarters, Dhaka Cantonment - 12th BMA Long Course\n# Major General Waqar-uz-Zaman \u2013 Military Secretary ('''MS'''), Army Headquarters, Dhaka Cantonment <ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.banglanews24.com/english/national/article/59325/Major-changes-in-top-positions-of-army|title=Major changes in top positions of army|last=http://www.banglanews24.com|website=www.banglanews24.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> - 13th BMA Long Course\n# Major General [[Ibne Fazal Shayekhuzzaman]] \u2013 [[Engineer-in-Chief (Bangladesh army)|Engineer-in-Chief